commentTextItems.html: plays back to a length ball and gone, nicks off! A feisty last-wicket stand is ended by Morkel, bowling a tight line on off, Patel was stuck on the crease and prodded at the ball to be caught at the wicket - which means South Africa win by 80 runs

commentPostTextItems.html: 8.30pm: England captain, Alastair Cook: "We just didn't play very well, in all three aspects. All credit to the way Amla played, his innings showed us how to play. When we batted we were up with the run rate but we never got our partnerships going. Amla played beautifully, it's frustrating for a captain. It's frustrating to drop catches, we're training really hard but they're not sticking. There's no reason why they're going down. We thought it was gettable but we needed someone to stay in and get big runs. It hasn't happened today and it's frustrating but we've got three games to come. They're playing some good cricket, we've got to look within ourselves to do it, players have got to stand up and be counted to turn it around."

South Africa captain, AB de Villiers: "Yeah, very happy, though still think there's a few areas we can work on. I enjoyed the South Africa support out there today. There's still stuff we can work on to get better, Hashim's on fire at the moment, he's breaking all sorts of records and hopefully that can continue well into the future. We were just trying different combinations, left-hand, right-hand combinations against the spinners, we change things [with the order] according to the situation. The wicket played well, we thought it might break up a bit more but the spinners did well. We lost wickets at quick intervals in the middle, fielding wasn't perfect, so lots to work on. We're proud [of being No. 1] but there are lost of ODIs played and we're working towards winning a World Cup and staying No. 1."

Hashim Amla is named Man of the Match: "Things are falling into place but an element of fortune has to go your way as well and I just try to stick to the basics. The one-day game has its different characteristics and you can play a few more flair shots. The wicket was tough early on and it was tough to score off the spinners, the pace was down but we got our partnerships going. I didn't think I would be achieving this, it's just an honour. I'm enjoying the game and the team results have been fantastic and that takes precedence. My circus moment [in the field] just tweaked my back but I'll rest it and hopefully be okay for The Oval."
Right, that's your lot for tonight (and not even a drop of rain to lubricate things). Gnasher and I will be back for the third one-dayer on Friday - we hope you will be too. Cheerio

8.20pm: It was never in doubt, even when Steven Finn and Samit Patel were slogging from the hip. Victory means South Africa take a 1-0 lead in the series, as well as leap-frog England to take No. 1 spot in the ODI rankings. A first ODI defeat of 2012 means England actually slip to third, behind India, though there are still three matches in the series to play. Hashim Amla, for it was he, laid the foundations - and what mighty foundations they were - on a pitch that was far more difficult to score on than he made it look; England lost wickets at regular intervals and in the end lost by a wide margin. Gnasher's report is waiting to pored over and I'll be back with the presentations shortly.

commentTextItems.html: full and wide of off, steps away and thrashes the ball back down the ground to long-off
length ball outside off, steered behind point and du Plessis effects a direct hit but Finn is home

commentPreTextItems.html: England need 84 from the last ten. Fancy it?

attacks again, not cleanly struck and the ball loops over cover for a couple

commentTextItems.html: nailed over deep midwicket! This is right out the screws, a lot of bottom hand and that's six more - Patel is taking a leaf out of Finn's book
tossed up outside off and scooped over extra-cover, the arms swinging freely for Patel now
Patel advances again and this time lofts the ball all the way over long-off with a mighty swing of the blade
tossed up and turned calmly towards midwicket for a single
tossed up on middle, Patel gives it the charge and slogs down the ground ... but long-off gets to the ball and they only pick up one
yorker in response from Morkel, hits Finn on the pad but it was missing leg

length ball outside off, steps away and bullets the ball through cover for a freewheeling four

headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Bresnan player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Graeme Smith c Kieswetter b Bresnan 52 (76b 5x4 0x6 82m) SR: 68.42

dismissalComment.html: swings across the line, top-edged ... and gone! Bresnan has broken through, banging it in short as Smith skipped down the pitch, he tried to hook but the ball ballooned high into the air, over the wicketkeeper, with Kieswetter running back to settle underneath and take a safe catch

headshotImage.caption: Graeme Swann player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Graeme Swann player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jean-Paul Duminy run out (Anderson) 14 (24b 1x4 0x6 27m) SR: 58.33

dismissalComment.html: Amla calls for one but it isn't there and Duminy is run out! It was clipped through the leg side from outside off, Amla thought it had beaten midwicket and set off only for Anderson to reel the ball in and hurl it to Kieswetter, Duminy wasn't even in the picture, though he is sacrificed in favour of the senior man

dismissalText.commentary: Dean Elgar b Swann 15 (28b 1x4 0x6 29m) SR: 53.57

dismissalComment.html: gone! Lovely bowling. Tossed up slower by Swann, it gripped off the surface and spun past the outside edge to take middle stump

headshotImage.caption: Graeme Swann player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Graeme Swann player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: AB de Villiers b Swann 28 (29b 1x4 0x6 43m) SR: 96.55

dismissalComment.html: bowled him! De Villiers advanced as Swann sent down a non-turner, it dipped late on the batsman, who played across the line and the ball skittered through low to thump into the base of off stump. Swann gets his man after an over's reprieve

headshotImage.caption: Tim Bresnan player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Bresnan player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Hashim Amla c Bresnan b Finn 150 (124b 16x4 0x6 209m) SR: 120.96

dismissalComment.html: short and slow, Amla backs away and tries to ramp the ball over short third man but it hasn't got enough pace on it and Bresnan pouches. After another everyday display of magnificence, Amla departs

dismissalText.commentary: Alastair Cook b Tsotsobe 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 4m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: gone! What a start for South Africa. Tsotsobe produces a superb yorker which spears under Cook's bat and takes out the off stump.

headshotImage.caption: Robin Peterson player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Robin Peterson player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ian Bell b Peterson 45 (41b 5x4 0x6 74m) SR: 109.75

dismissalComment.html: a beauty bowls Bell! Peterson gave it a rip, the ball pitching in line with off and straightening sharply, Bell played inside the line and had his off stump pegged back. It was very similar to the ball from Patel that shaved Amla's off stump ... but a smidge better, obviously

headshotImage.longCaption: Jonathan Trott player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.longCaption: Jonathan Trott player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.longCaption: Dean Elgar player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jonathan Trott c Elgar b Morkel 23 (37b 2x4 0x6 52m) SR: 62.16

dismissalComment.html: scooped hiiiiiiiiiiiiiiigh towards long leg ... and Elgar takes a fantastic catch over his shoulder to remove Trott! It looked like he had misjudged it, having come in off the rope, but backpedalled quickly and hurled himself full length to get his hands underneath it. Very composed, ahem, from Elgar

headshotImage.caption: Robin Peterson player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Robin Peterson player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ravi Bopara c du Plessis b Peterson 16 (21b 2x4 0x6 30m) SR: 76.19

dismissalComment.html: oh, gone! Bopara slaps a rank long hop straight to extra-cover! He'll be joining the queue to kick himself after that dismissal, having apparently played himself in only to thump a loose delivery down the throat of Faf du Plessis

headshotImage.caption: Dean Elgar player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Dean Elgar player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Eoin Morgan c Elgar b Duminy 27 (48b 1x4 0x6 77m) SR: 56.25

dismissalComment.html: gone! That's the game you'd think. Morgan can't believe it as he pulls a short ball straight to deep midwicket. Not Morgan's most fluent innings by a long way. Good work from AB de Villiers with the field setting

dismissalText.commentary: Craig Kieswetter c Smith b Elgar 20 (20b 1x4 1x6 19m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: more turn for Elgar and that's done for Kieswetter, caught at slip via a deflection off AB! Kieswetter tried to close the face to leg, was done by the spin and the ball kissed the back of the bat, de Villiers couldn't take it but Smith was alert as the ball popped up off the keeper's gloves

dismissalText.commentary: Samit Patel c de Villiers b Morkel 45 (51b 3x4 2x6 75m) SR: 88.23

dismissalComment.html: plays back to a length ball and gone, nicks off! A feisty last-wicket stand is ended by Morkel, bowling a tight line on off, Patel was stuck on the crease and prodded at the ball to be caught at the wicket - which means South Africa win by 80 runs

videos.summary: Hashim Amla's 150 helped South Africa ease to an 80-run victory over England in the second one-day international in Southampton on Tuesday, and climb to No. 1 in the rankings as a result
